  "prompt": "Is there a Church that doesn't believe in Trinity?",
  "response": "Yes, there are Christian churches and denominations that do not adhere to the doctrine of the Trinity, which is the belief that God exists as three persons\u2014Father, Son (Jesus Christ), and Holy Spirit\u2014in one divine being. These non-Trinitarian groups have alternative understandings of the nature of God and Jesus Christ. Some examples include:\n\n1. **Unitarianism**: Unitarian Christians generally believe in the unity of God and reject the concept of the Trinity. They often view Jesus as a great teacher and prophet but not as divine in the same way as the Father.\n\n2. **Jehovah's Witnesses**: This denomination teaches that Jehovah (God the Father) is the one true God, while Jesus is viewed as His first creation and the Holy Spirit as God's active force, not a distinct person.\n\n3. **The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church/Mormons)**: Mormons believe in the Father, Son, and Holy Spirit as three distinct beings united in purpose, rather than one being in three persons. They also have unique beliefs about the nature of God and Jesus.\n\n4. **Oneness Pentecostalism**: Oneness Pentecostals believe in the oneness of God and see Jesus as both fully divine and fully human, rejecting the traditional Trinitarian formulation. They emphasize baptism in Jesus' name rather than in the name of the Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.\n\n5. **Christadelphians**: This group believes in the unity of God and rejects the Trinity. They view Jesus as the Son of God but not as part of a triune Godhead.\n\n6. **The Way International**: This group teaches that there is one God and rejects the Trinity, emphasizing the teachings of the Apostle Paul.\n\n7. **Some Restorationist Groups**: Certain Restorationist movements, particularly those influenced by early American religious thought, reject the Trinity in favor of a more unitary view of God.\n\nThese groups often interpret scripture differently from mainstream Trinitarian Christianity and emphasize a different understanding of the relationship between God, Jesus, and the Holy Spirit.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
